            <handDesc>
              <handNote scope="major" script="syr" medium="">
                <desc>This volume is written in a rather peculiar hand of the xiith or xiiith cent.,
                  with the exception of foll. 44 and 268, which are somewhat more modern. </desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote scope="minor" script="syr" medium="">
                <desc>A later hand has inserted two lessons from the Pauline Epistles; viz. a) from
                  1 Corinthians, ch. xii. 28—xiii. 10, fol. 43 b; and b) from Romans, ch. viii.
                  28—39, fol. 44 b.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote scope="minor" script="syr" medium="">
                <desc>Fol. 268 contains a ܣܘܓܝܬܐ for the Resurrection, written by a different
                  hand.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote scope="minor" script="syr" medium="">
                <desc>The prayer on fol. 2 a is apparently in the same handwriting as the note by
                  the priest Ibrahim or Abraham.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote scope="minor" script="Mixed" medium="">
                <desc>On fol. 268b there is a note in Syriac and Arabic by a priest named Ibrahim or
                  Abraham.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote scope="minor" script="Mixed" medium="">
                <desc>There is another note on 268b from a priest named Daniel in Syriac, Latin, and
                  Arabic.</desc>
              </handNote>
            </handDesc>
            <additions>
              <p></p>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <locus from="268b" to=""/>
                  <p>On fol. 268 b there is a note in Syriac and Arabic, by a priest named<persName>
                      Ibrāhīm or Abraham</persName>, dated <origDate>A. Gr. 1558</origDate>,
                      <origDate>A.D. 1247.</origDate> The Arabic text is the better preserved.</p>
                  <p><quote xml:lang="ar">القس ابرهيم من ال .... سنه الف وخمسمايه وثمنيه وخمسين من سنين لاسكندر ابن
                      اليوناني في عشين يوم من حٍٍ[زيران] يوم الثلثه ء....</quote></p>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <locus from="268b" to=""/>
                  <p>There is another note on fol. 268 b, in which the priest
                      <persName>Daniel</persName>, from the village of
                      <placeName>Hagūlī,</placeName> mentions that he read this volume twice, once
                      at<placeName> Haguli</placeName>, and again at the village of
                      <placeName>Benīsa</placeName>. </p>
                  <p>
                    <quote xml:lang="syr">ܦܓ̣ܥ ܒܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ ܘܩܪܝ ܒܗ ܒܩܪܝܬܐ ܚܓܘܠܝ. ܘܬܘܒ ܙܒܢ̣ܬܐ ܐܚܪܝܬܐ
                      ܒܩܪܝܬܐ ܒܢܝܣܗ ܩܫܝܫܐ ܕܢܝܐܝܠ ܕܡܢ ܚܓܘܠܝ. ܨ̈ܠܘ ܥܠܝ ܒܒܥܘ ܡܛܠ ܡܫܝܚܐ.</quote>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <quote xml:lang="la">amen micerere mei deus </quote>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <quote xml:lang="ar">لاهم اغفر لعبدك المدعيا القس دنيال</quote>
                  </p>
                </item>
              </list>
            </additions>
